Citation.sAbstract: Experimental results are reported for the solubility of a-carotene in six binary mixed solvents formed by 2,5,8-  trioxanonane with 1-hexene, cyclohexane, hexane, and toluene and by 1-hexene with 2-propanone and  cyclohexanone at 293.15 K. A spectral colorimeter was used for analysis of a-carotene concentration. The a-carotene  solubility in the pure solvents increases in the order: 2-propanone less than hexane less than 2,5,8-trioxanonane less than 1-hexene  less than cyclohexane less than cyclohexanone less than toluene. The solubility data as a function of the binary solvent mass fractions  were smoothed by the Myers and Scott equation for asymmetric functions. The Flory and Huggins theory of  non-athermal mixtures and the Acree and Rytting model were used for prediction of experimental data for the  solubility of a-carotene in the six binary above listed mixed solvents.
Citation.sTitle: Solubility of a-Carotene in Binary Solvents Formed by Some Hydrocarbons with 2,5,8-Trioxanonane, 2-Propanone, and Cyclohexanone
